  "grammar": [
    {
      "id": "g-0005",
      "type": "grammar",
      "topic": "Subject–Verb Agreement (tricky cases)",
      "cefr": "B2",
      "tags": ["agreement", "weak-spot"],
      "explanationMd": "## Subject–Verb Agreement (tricky cases)\n\nThe verb must match the **real subject**, not the nearest noun.\n\n### one of the + plural noun → singular verb\nThe subject is *one*, not the plural noun after it.\n> **One of the students is** absent. (not *are*)\n\n### each / every / everyone → singular\n> **Each of us has** a task. / **Everyone is** ready.\n\n### neither / either → singular\n> **Neither answer is** correct.\n\n### Don't be fooled by words between subject and verb\n> The **box** of chocolates **is** on the table. (subject = box)\n\n### Common mistakes\n- ❌ *One of my friends are a doctor.*\n- ✅ *One of my friends is a doctor.*",
      "exercises": [
        {
          "id": "g-0005-e1",
          "type": "fill_blank",
          "prompt": "One of the windows ______ (be) broken.",
          "answer": "is",
          "accepted": ["is"],
          "explanationMd": "Subject is *one* → singular verb **is**."
        },
        {
          "id": "g-0005-e2",
          "type": "error_correction",
          "prompt": "Each of the players have a number.",
          "answer": "Each of the players has a number.",
          "explanationMd": "*Each* takes a **singular** verb (has)."
        },
        {
          "id": "g-0005-e3",
          "type": "multiple_choice",
          "prompt": "The box of old letters ______ in the attic.",
          "options": ["are", "is", "were", "have"],
          "answer": "is",
          "explanationMd": "Subject = *box* (singular), not *letters*."
        },
        {
          "id": "g-0005-e4",
          "type": "sentence_build",
          "prompt": "Build: (one / my / of / cousins / lives / in / Canada)",
          "answer": "One of my cousins lives in Canada."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "g-0006",
      "type": "grammar",
      "topic": "First & Second Conditional",
      "cefr": "B1",
      "tags": ["conditionals", "weak-spot"],
      "explanationMd": "## First & Second Conditional\n\n### First conditional — real / likely future\n**Structure:** `If + present simple, will + verb`\n> **If I sleep** well, I **will feel** better tomorrow.\n\nUse for things that can really happen.\n\n### Second conditional — unreal / imaginary present\n**Structure:** `If + past simple, would + verb`\n> **If I had** more time, I **would exercise** daily.\n\nUse for imaginary or unlikely situations. With *be*, use **were** for all subjects:\n> If I **were** you, I'd rest.\n\n### Common mistakes\n- ❌ *If I will see him, I will tell him.*\n- ✅ *If I see him, I will tell him.* (no *will* in the if-clause)",
      "exercises": [
        {
          "id": "g-0006-e1",
          "type": "fill_blank",
          "prompt": "If it rains tomorrow, we ______ (stay) at home.",
          "answer": "will stay",
          "accepted": ["will stay", "'ll stay"],
          "explanationMd": "First conditional: *if + present, **will + verb***."
        },
        {
          "id": "g-0006-e2",
          "type": "error_correction",
          "prompt": "If I would have time, I would travel more.",
          "answer": "If I had time, I would travel more.",
          "explanationMd": "Second conditional uses **past simple** in the if-clause, never *would*."
        },
        {
          "id": "g-0006-e3",
          "type": "multiple_choice",
          "prompt": "If I ______ you, I would start today.",
          "options": ["am", "was", "were", "be"],
          "answer": "were",
          "explanationMd": "Second conditional with *be* uses **were** for all subjects."
        },
        {
          "id": "g-0006-e4",
          "type": "sentence_build",
          "prompt": "Build: (if / you / early / sleep / you / better / will / feel)",
          "answer": "If you sleep early, you will feel better."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "g-0007",
      "type": "grammar",
      "topic": "Reported Speech",
      "cefr": "B2",
      "tags": ["reported-speech"],
      "explanationMd": "## Reported Speech\n\nWhen you report what someone said, the tense usually **shifts back** one step.\n\n### Tense backshift\n- present simple → past simple: *\"I **am** tired\"* → He said he **was** tired.\n- present continuous → past continuous: *\"I **am working**\"* → She said she **was working**.\n- past simple → past perfect: *\"I **saw** it\"* → He said he **had seen** it.\n- will → would: *\"I **will** call\"* → She said she **would** call.\n\n### Pronouns & time words also change\n*\"I'll see you **tomorrow**\"* → He said he would see me **the next day**.\n\n### Common mistakes\n- ❌ *She said she is tired.*\n- ✅ *She said she was tired.*",
      "exercises": [
